    "recap_headline": "Baylor",
    "recap_text": "WACO, Texas \u2013\nBaylor baseball dropped the middle game of its three-game series with No. 22 West Virginia, 13-2, in seven innings on Saturday at Magnolia Field at Baylor Ballpark.\nThe Bears (11-7, 1-1) were unable to find much momentum offensively outside of a two-run home run from redshirt senior first baseman\nTyce Armstrong\n. WVU (12-4, 1-1) held BU to just two runs on three hits, while the Mountaineers racked up 13 runs on 17 hits on the day.\nTHE RUNDOWN\nWest Virginia got on the board right away with three runs on three hits and three walks in the top of the first. The Bears turned a nifty 5-4-3 double play to prevent further damage in the opening frame.\nIn the second, WVU kept rolling with five more hits and another three runs, extending its lead to 6-0. After a scoreless third, the Mountaineers tacked on one more in the fourth on an RBI fielder's choice.\nBU chipped away at the deficit in the home half of the fourth as freshman outfielder\nBrady Janusek\nsingled up the middle and later scored on Armstrong's two-run shot, his seventh of the year.\nHowever, WVU got those runs right back with two in the top of the fifth to move the scoreline to 9-2. In the sixth, the visitors kept adding on with another three runs and held the Bears' bats quiet in the home half. West Virginia plated one more in the top of the seventh and retired the BU side in the bottom half to complete the run-rule victory.\nHIGHLIGHTS\n\u2022 With one stolen base on the day, Baylor increased its total to 29 through 18 games in 2026, its most at this point in a single season since 2011 (36).\n\u2022 Redshirt junior INF\nTravis Sanders\nextended his on-base streak to 23 games, dating back to 2025.\n\u2022 Freshman OF\nBrady Janusek\nhas reached safely in all 18 games so far this year.\n\u2022 Redshirt senior 1B\nTyce Armstrong\nextended his hitting streak to five games.\n\u2022 Armstrong also launched his team-leading seventh home run of the season and tallied his fourth multi-RBI game of the season.\n\u2022 Redshirt freshman OF\nHunter Snow\nextended his hitting streak to six games.\n\u2022 Junior C\nJJ Kennett\nextended his on-base streak to 11 games, dating back to 2025.\n\u2022 Senior RHP\nCade Hansen\nrecorded a season-high four strikeouts on the mound.\n\u2022 Redshirt freshman RHP\nBrayden Bergman\nworked his third multi-strikeout outing of the year.\nSTAT OF THE DAY\n7 \u2013 Redshirt senior first baseman\nTyce Armstrong\nhit his seventh home run of the season, a two-run shot that accounted for both Baylor runs on the day.\nQUOTABLE\nHead Coach\nMitch Thompson\nOn takeaways from today's game\u2026\n\"We didn't kick it, we just didn't pitch it well enough. Our guys are out there trying. We've got to get a couple guys cleaned up, gotta keep working on figuring out how to get something out of a couple guys that are capable of helping us. But we were competing. Our at-bats weren't bad. Those guys are really good on Saturdays, his [WVU starter Chansen Cole] numbers are outstanding. And what you saw today was the value of starting pitching. Here we are, on a short leash because of our situation with our starters, trying out somebody that hasn't started yet. And, you know, tomorrow we'll run a starter out there and we'll hopefully get deeper into the game and have a shot to be in it and win it.\"\nWHAT'S NEXT\nBaylor (11-7, 1-1) and No. 22 West Virginia (12-4, 1-1) close out the weekend series with a rubber match on Sunday, March 15, at 11 a.m. from Magnolia Field at Baylor Ballpark in Waco.\nTo stay up to date on all things Baylor baseball, follow the team on its official Facebook, Twitter and Instagram accounts: @BaylorBaseball.\n-BaylorBears.com-"
